{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489829"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:31:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:31:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"751"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/751"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.35,0.18,0.38,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"751"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103735"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/751"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"751"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86156"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"526"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35579"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35609"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103735"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man is reviewed on an orthopaedic ward with a three-day history of abdominal distension and constipation. He has not passed flatus or faeces for three days. He underwent a right total hip replacement five days ago and has otherwise been making good progress. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his abdomen is distended and soft, with tenderness in the right lower quadrant. Bowel sounds are scant. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. A plain abdominal X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transverse loop colostomy","Colonoscopic decompression","Neostigmine","Decompression with a flatus tube","Sigmoid colectomy and end-colostomy (Hartmann procedure)"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms consistent with pseudo-obstruction, a recognised complication of pelvic and hip surgery. The abdominal X-ray shows a large gas-filled loop of transverse colon, confirming the diagnosis of Ogilvie\u0027s syndrome (acute colonic pseudo-obstruction). In most instances these cases can be managed conservatively. Given the patient\u0027s clinical presentation and imaging findings, some form of active intervention is required. The patient symptoms have been going on for at least two days and there is evidence of localised peritonism. Ie if nothing is done, the risk of perforation is high. \u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopic decompression\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EColonoscopic decompression is the first-line treatment for pseudo-obstruction when there is significant colonic distension or concerning clinical signs, such as the right lower quadrant tenderness, in this case. It allows for direct visualisation of the colon and effective removal of gas and fluid. This procedure can be repeated if necessary until the pseudo-obstruction resolves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransverse loop colostomy\u003C/strong\u003E is an overly invasive approach for initial management of pseudo-obstruction. Surgical intervention is typically reserved for cases where conservative measures and colonoscopic decompression have failed, or if there are signs of bowel ischaemia or perforation, such as peritonitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeostigmine\u003C/strong\u003E, a cholinesterase inhibitor, can be effective in treating pseudo-obstruction. However, it is contraindicated when there is concern about over-distension or ischemia. It also requires cardiac monitoring due to the risk of profound bradycardia so is often given in an ICU setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecompression with a flatus tube\u003C/strong\u003E is less effective than colonoscopic decompression for significant colonic distension. It may be attempted in milder cases or as an adjunct to other treatments, but it is not the most appropriate first-line management in this scenario. The predominant distended section in this X-ray is also more proximal than a flatus tube would reach\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESigmoid colectomy and end-colostomy (Hartmann procedure)\u003C/strong\u003E is an emergency treatment for obstructing lesions in the sigmoid colon or upper rectum. It is not indicated for pseudo-obstruction and would be an unnecessarily aggressive approach in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing pseudo-obstruction, it is important to note that the risk of bowel wall compromise increases significantly when the caecal diameter exceeds 11 cm. Serial abdominal X-rays can help monitor the progression of distension. Additionally, addressing contributing factors such as opiates and anticholinergics, and ensuring adequate hydration and electrolyte balance, are important aspects of comprehensive management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Colonoscopic decompression is the first-line treatment for pseudo-obstruction with significant colonic distension and signs of peritonism.","Pseudo-obstruction is a recognised complication of pelvic and hip surgery, often exacerbated by opiates and anticholinergics.","Caecal diameter exceeding 11 cm significantly increases the risk of bowel wall compromise in pseudo-obstruction."],"references":["Mankaney G, Sarvepalli S, Arora Z, et al. Colonic Decompression Reduces Proximal Acute Colonic Pseudo-obstruction and Related Symptoms. Dis Colon Rectum. 2020; 63:60-67. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31567918/","Khan Z, Challand CP, Lee MJ. Management of acute colonic pseudo-obstruction: opportunities to improve care? Ann R Coll Surg Engl 2025; 107: 106\u201311"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86156"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"751"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17555"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17555"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e074799c-544a-4903-b2b1-fffbf55d2ec4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e074799c-544a-4903-b2b1-fffbf55d2ec4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":351,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86156"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-26T10:16:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-26T10:16:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"751"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103735"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"ite